Pictures have emerged of pupils in Malanga outside of Dundee in KwaZulu-Natal, crossing a river to get to school. KZN Education MEC Kwazi Mshengu spoke on what will be done to ensure the safety of the children. Courtesy #DStv403 DUNDEE - Pictures have emerged on social media of pupils in Malanga, outside of Dundee, crossing a river in waist-high waters. Several students in one picture are seen crossing the waist-high uMzinyathi River. READ: KZN schools struggle with utility bills The photographs were first thought to have been taken approximately nine years ago but new information emerged that the problems had not yet been solved. The provincial education department has set up a task team to look into instances where school pupils have to wade through water. READ: Cogta says 'no money' to fix KZN storm-damaged schools KwaZulu-Natal Education MEC Kwazi Mshengu said the pictures are a reflection of the enduring socio-economic challenges facing most of the rural areas in Kwa-Zulu Natal. Mshengu said one of the pervasive problems confronted by the department is there is no comprehensive record of all the schools whose pupils have to cross rivers to attend classes. He stated that with an exhaustive list of the schools needing intervention, the Department could be proactive in assisting those in need.